%p
  embadge.io is a simple Ember.js community badge service.
  It's inspired by Matthew Beale's
  %a{:href => "https://github.com/mixonic/ember-community-versions"} Ember Community Versions
  and is open-sourced
  %a{:href => "https://github.com/halfdan/embadge.io"} on Github
%p
  Create a badge, embed it in your post, maintain it and let the community update the badge when its information is out of date.
%p
  %a{class:"btn", href: '/auth/github'}
    %span{class:"fa fa-github"}
    Sign in with Github


%h2#static Static Badges
%p In case you want to use a static badge and specify version information yourself, you can use the embadge.io API. It supports four different parameters.

%dl.dl-horizontal
  %dt label
  %dd Used to define the text label shown on the badge (default: 'ember-versions')

  %dt start
  %dd Valid semver string noting the earliest supported version.

  %dt end
  %dd (Optional) Valid semver string noting the last supported version.

  %dt range
  %dd (Optional) Valid semver range (e.g. "^2.3.0") noting a supported range of versions. If given, "start" and "end" will be ignored

%p The API supports HTTPS and is accessed from is
%code https://embadge.io/v1/badge.svg

%h2#examples Examples
%dl.dl-horizontal
  %dt Start version
  %dd
    %a{:href => "/v1/badge.svg?start=1.13.0"}
      %img{:src => "/v1/badge.svg?start=1.13.0"}/
  %dt Start and end version
  %dd
    %a{:href => "/v1/badge.svg?start=1.13.0&end=2.0.0"}
      %img{:src => "/v1/badge.svg?start=1.13.0&end=2.0.0"}/
  %dt Range
  %dd
    %a{:href => "/v1/badge.svg?range=^2.3.0"}
      %img{:src => "/v1/badge.svg?range=^2.3.0"}/
  %dt Custom label
  %dd
    %a{:href => "/v1/badge.svg?label=ember-cli&start=1.13.13"}
      %img{:src => "/v1/badge.svg?label=ember-cli&start=1.13.13"}/
  %dt Custom label & range
  %dd
    %a{:href => "/v1/badge.svg?label=ember-data&range=^2.3.0"}
      %img{:src => "/v1/badge.svg?label=ember-data&range=^2.3.0"}/

%h3#browser Browser
%p In order to easily add embadge.io to your website you can include the following script in the body:
%code
  &lt;script src="//embadge.io/v1/badge.js" type="text/javascript"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;
%br/
%br/
%p
  This will search your page for
  %code span
  elements with the
  %code embadge
  class and use data attributes to generate the image URL.
%code
  &lt;span class="embadge" data-start="2.3.0"&gt;&t;span&gt;
